archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: April 15, 2014
archive.description: Lawmakers scramble  as time runs out on the final meeting of the 2014 legislative session.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: April 14, 2014
archive.description: State House members discuss sexual harassment complaints and clamp down on the legislative ethics commission.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: March 31, 2014
archive.description: A shouting match unfolded during the contentious budget negotiations, but a  plan was finally reached for the biennial $20 billion state budget plan.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: March 28, 2014
archive.description: Budget negotiations are still ongoing as the third day of talks was punctuated with some tense moments.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: March 27, 2014
archive.description: A stalemate continues on the nearly $20 billion Executive Branch budget, but a long-awaited resolution regarding school snow days is reached.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: March 26, 2014
archive.description: A medical marijuana-related bill is almost to the finish line, and budget negotiations begin in earnest.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: March 25, 2014
archive.description: The Senate passes a rival revenue measure to the House plan.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: March 24, 2014
archive.description: The Republican controlled Senate marks up the state's 2-year spending plan and puts more limits on debt and borrowing.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: March 21, 2014
archive.description: A bill clarifying that the Bluegrass Pipeline cannot exercise the power of eminent domain clears the House.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: March 20, 2014
archive.description: A sweeping juvenile justice measure to keep kids from being locked up for status offenses like truancy makes it halfway to the legislative finish line.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: March 19, 2014
archive.description: A Republican leader's plan to shorten the legislative session is bound for the Democrat-controlled House, and a medical marijuana bill to help pediatric seizure patients advances.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: March 18, 2014
archive.description: The state transportation budget and highway construction plans advance, and so does a measure to let federal office holders run for reelection and president at the same time.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: March 17, 2014
archive.description: Another proposal to address missed school days because of bad weather is fast tracked in the Senate.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: March 14, 2014
archive.description: The House votes to let school districts waive up to 10 missed days because of bad weather.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: March 13, 2014
archive.description: The state budget bill debate gets weighed down in a parliamentary brawl on measures dealing with Obamacare and a federal ruling on gay marriage.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: March 12, 2014
archive.description: House leadership delays a vote on the 20.3 billion dollar spending plan, while other measures advance that will truncate session work days and let Kentucky's junior senator make a play for two offices at once.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: March 11, 2014
archive.description: The House Democrats' markup of the two year state budget is ready for a floor vote.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: March 10, 2014
archive.description: The Kentucky Senate debates a pilot project to open juvenile court proceedings.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: March 7, 2014
archive.description: Bills to keep rapists from visiting or getting custody of children conceived from the sexual assault they committed are covered.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: March 6, 2014
archive.description: Adult abuse protections, child health hazards, defeat of a prevailing wage measure, and more are covered.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: March 5, 2014
archive.description: Demonstrators clamor to the capital for celebration and activation on a felon voting rights bill, and a bill extending civil rights to gays gets its first hearing.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: March 4, 2014
archive.description: Reaction to the Governor's announcement to appeal a federal ruling on gay marriage in Kentucky is covered.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: February 28, 2014
archive.description: The House takes on distracted driving and concealed weapons for domestic abuse victims.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: February 27, 2014
archive.description: Opening certain juvenile court proceedings and decriminalizing medical marijuana dominated the action.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: February 26, 2014
archive.description: A bill advances which legalizes limited use of cannabis oil to control seizures, and a House committee pushes through a contentious eminent domain measure directed at the Bluegrass Pipeline project.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: February 25, 2014
archive.description: Protecting nursing home patients with employee background checks, and keeping motorists from using phones in school and construction zones are covered.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: February 24, 2014
archive.description: Lawmakers want to clarify that state law doesn't allow private developers of natural gas liquid pipelines to exercise the power of eminent domain.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: February 21, 2014
archive.description: State leaders are eager to get to work on the state budget.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: February 20, 2014
archive.description: Guns in bars, cops on boats, and protecting vulnerable adults are covered.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: February 19, 2014
archive.description: The midpoint of the session is marked with a long day on voting rights and medical malpractice.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: February 18, 2014
archive.description: A bill to charge Medicaid no-show patients is discussed.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: February 14, 2014
archive.description: An early childhood education measure consumed the legislative docket today.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: February 13, 2014
archive.description: Bills to keep kids safe in the car and online advance in the state legislature.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: February 12, 2014
archive.description: Tense moments in the state legislature over a gay marriage ruling, medical review panels, and centralized voting are highlighted.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: February 11, 2014
archive.description: Tax reform, child passenger safety, and sending a message against international environmental policy are covered.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: February 10, 2014
archive.description: The Kentucky Senate tries to put more teeth in a measure addressing landlord liability when a renter's dog has more bark than bite.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: February 7, 2014
archive.description: Legislators get Gov. Beshear's tax reform plan and toe the party line on increasing the state minimum wage.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: February 6, 2014
archive.description: The House votes on boosting the state minimum wage.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: February 5, 2014
archive.description: The Kentucky Senate votes to expand informed consent for abortion by requiring ultrasound before the procedure.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: February 4, 2014
archive.description: Gov. Beshear unveils his tax reform plan that makes suggestions at modernization.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: February 3, 2014
archive.description: Gov. Beshear pitches a proposal that represents the largest single investment in the Kentucky community and technical college system since its formation.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: Jan. 31, 2014
archive.description: A recap of education matters, limiting gubernatorial powers, and a telecommunications measure.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: Jan. 30, 2014
archive.description: A telecommunications deregulation bill advances.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: Jan. 29, 2014
archive.description: Felony expungement and nuclear power were discussed.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: Jan. 28, 2014
archive.description: The state  budget director reiterates the governor's main budgetary objective: invest in education.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: Jan. 27, 2014
archive.description: Letting school staff receive training to administer insulin to students was considered in the state legislature.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: Jan. 24, 2014
archive.description: A bill dealing with waste in the food chain and a recapping of this week of legislating are covered.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: Jan. 23, 2014
archive.description: A bill to let lawmakers opt out of substantially larger pensions when they later take a judgeship or work in the executive branch clears the Kentucky Senate.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: Jan. 22, 2014
archive.description: The Kentucky Senate debates informed consent for abortion, the rescheduling of the election of the governor, and expanded gambling.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: Jan. 21, 2014
archive.description: Governor Steve Beshear lays out his spending priorities to a joint session of the Kentucky House and Senate.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: Jan. 17, 2014
archive.description: A roundup of the week's legislative topics including a bill to let voters decide if ex-cons should have their voting rights restored are highlighted.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: Jan. 16, 2014
archive.description: A bill to get reckless high volume heroine dealers behind bars and voting rights for ex-cons are highlighted.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: Jan. 15, 2014
archive.description: Gambling expansion in the Commonweath, reining in legislative pensions, and changing the date when the governor and other officers are elected are covered.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: Jan. 14, 2014
archive.description: Automatic voting rights restoration for certain former felons, legislation for impact investors, and prescriptive authority for advanced nurses are covered.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: Jan. 13, 2014
archive.description: A call to examine the child welfare system and its response to victims.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: Jan. 10, 2014
archive.description: A call to shun partisanship in order to take care of the people of Kentucky.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: Jan. 9, 2014
archive.description: Emotional outbursts from advocates for medicinal marijuana in Kentucky punctuate a legislative hearing on legalization.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: Jan. 8, 2014
archive.description: Advocates for victims of domestic violence rally around a bill to protect those in dating relationships and smoke-free legislation picks up steam.

archive.title: Legislative Update
archive.subtitle: Jan. 7, 2014
archive.description: Highlights of day one of the 2014 General Assembly and the Governor's State of the Commonwealth Address are covered.
